TUBERCULOSIS, ELEPHANTS - USA (02): (OREGON) UPDATE
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 11 Jun 2014
Source: Katu, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.katu.com/news/local/Tusko-becomes-third-elephant-at-Oregon-Zoo-to-contract--262725581.html


Tests have confirmed tuberculosis in Tusko, the 3rd elephant at the Oregon Zoo in Portland [Oregon] with the respiratory disease.

Veterinarians are beginning an 18-month treatment regimen for the 44-year-old male Asian elephant. 2 other bull elephants, Packy and Rama, are being treated for TB that was diagnosed last year [2013] at the zoo.

The zoo said Tuesday [10 Jun 2014] that 4 female elephants and the 5-year-old male Samudra have all tested negative

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Tuberculosis (TB) caused by _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_ or _Mycobacterium bovis_ has recently re-emerged as an important infectious disease in zoo animals, particularly captive elephants. While TB has been recognized as a disease of elephants for over 20 centuries, increasing numbers of elephant TB cases have been reported in the past 2 decades. It has been reported that about 3 percent of captive elephants in the United States are infected with _M. tuberculosis_.

Portions of this comment were extracted from http://cvi.asm.org/content/13/7/722.full.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of the affected area can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2548517,31123. - Mod.PMB]
